        {
            "id": "for_vs_while",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**For loops vs While loops**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Use `for` loops when you know how many times you want to repeat the code. Use `while` loops when you want to repeat until a condition becomes `False`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "for_vs_while",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Lets look at a simple example of a `for` loop and a `while` loop to count from 0 to 3."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Using For loop**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "for i in range(4):\n    print(f\"Count: {i}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Count: 0\nCount: 1\nCount: 2\nCount: 3"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Using While loop**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "count = 0\nwhile count < 4:\n    print(f\"Count: {count}\")\n    count = count + 1",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Count: 0\nCount: 1\nCount: 2\nCount: 3"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Both loops do the same thing, but the `for` loop is simpler and less error-prone."
                }
            ]
        },
